npc1: I saw her. Three nodes back. I barely made it out.
npc1: She looks like static shaped into a person. Like a signal that forgot it was ever human.
npc1: She was reading a list when she found me. Names. Account numbers. Amounts outstanding. She reads it constantly, like a prayer.
npc1: I am not on her list. That is the only reason I am still here.
npc1: She cannot be reasoned with. She does not respond to pleas. Every argument I tried she answered with the same line: "The debt is valid. The debt is owed. The debt will be collected."
npc1: But here is what I learned from watching her.
npc1: She operates on the platform's own rules. And the platform's rules have a flaw — they were written by the Necromancer to trap people, not to survive scrutiny.
npc1: If you can expose the flaw in the contract — show that the debt was manufactured, that the odds were fixed, that consent was engineered — she loses her authority.
npc1: She is only as powerful as the rules she enforces. Break the rules and she breaks with them.
npc1: You need to reach the source. That is where the contracts live. That is where you can end this.
